{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9f511254-ae8a-4539-880c-c84afae9a4b3","content":"The working directory is empty, so I'll answer based on the skill-validator evaluation framework referenced in this repo's conventions.\n\n## Evaluation Format (`evaluation.yml`)\n\nEvaluations are defined in YAML. Each entry is a **natural-language user question** paired with **assertions** about what the LLM should do:\n\n```yaml\nevaluations:\n  - prompt: \"Find all products under $50 in the Electronics category\"\n    expectations:\n      - tool: search_products\n        arguments:\n          category: \"Electronics\"\n          maxPrice: 50\n\n  - prompt: \"What's the average rating for product ID 42?\"\n    expectations:\n      - tool: get_product_details\n        arguments:\n          productId: 42\n```\n\n## What Makes a Good Evaluation Question\n\n1. **Unambiguous intent** — The question should map clearly to one or more tool calls. Avoid prompts where the \"right\" tool is debatable.\n\n2. **Argument extraction** — Include specific values (IDs, prices, names) so you can assert the LLM extracted them correctly.\n\n3. **Multi-tool scenarios** — Test chained calls, e.g. *\"Compare prices of product 7 and product 12\"* → two `get_product_details` calls.\n\n4. **Edge cases** — Include prompts with missing optional params, ambiguous phrasing, or no matching tool to test graceful handling.\n\n5. **Realistic language** — Use natural phrasing a real user would type, not robotic descriptions of the tool's API.\n\n**Tip:** Start with 5–10 \"golden path\" questions covering each tool, then add edge cases. Run the skill-validator to see pass/fail results and iterate.\n\nWould you like me to scaffold an `evaluation.yml` file for your product catalog tools?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a0ce0683-b4f9-4d0c-a7a5-398c7cbfe544","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"1583:3BD7C9:3192157:363B23F:69FBE51F"},"id":"6f0c5cbe-a3db-4e09-8d43-33b950bb0147","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:04:43